description: Access to field 'name' results in a dereference of a null pointer (loaded from variable 'dn')

investigation.notes: Unsure if dn is NULL or dn->name is null and being dereferenced in print_name.  It looks like no for the latter.  If dn itself is NULL, then the -> will be an error.  Traced dn back to sort_and_display_files.  This creates dn from dnalloc, which can return null is its arg num is less than one.  If the loop on 931 is never entered, nfiles stays zero, which gets passed to dnalloc on 964, resulting in NULL dnp, set to subdnp on 1016, which cannot be passed on 1024, because it is blocked by nfiles > 0, the same condition the prevents dnp from being NULL.  Another call to dnalloc in ls_main on 1221 also cannot result in NULL, because 1196 initialies nfiles to 0, 1211 only increments it, and 1215 returns if nfiles is zero before calling dnalloc.

description: Dereference of null pointer

investigation.notes: Another one in ENABLE_FEATURE_GETOPT_LONG.  longopts is a possible culprit.  It is passed into generate_output from getopt_main, which only exists if ENABLE_FEATURE_GETOPT_LONG is enabled.  It is initialized to NULL.  (Possibly good example of variability bug).  If ENABLE_FEATURE_GETOPT_LONG is not enabled, getopt_main cannot even compile, because long_options is used outside of an ifdef, but declared inside an ifdef.  As for the bug, it seems that if the condition on 386 holds, then generate_output will get a NULL version of long_options.  (Funny that 220 defines a macro to remove the longopts argument from generate_output, which removes it from both the definition and the calls).  If longopts, passed from long_options to 224, is NULL, 239 and 240 should also fail (API error as NULL is passed to the unistd getopt_long[_only].

Use of memory after it is freed

investigation.notes: The use-after-free alert happens because dest is freed on line 227 and the loop allows dest to be used again on line 207.  dest is set to last on line 197.  208 woudl also be a use-after-free.  In order for this use to happen, neither of the loop exits (lines 211 and 224) would be triggered on the first iteration.  Given the comment on line 223, it seems that looping is possible.  This is a good example of a variability bug, since the use-after-free identified here can only happen when ENABLE_FEATURE_CP_LONG_OPTIONS (line 203).  I tcan't happen from 198, since the comment claims the loop will break on 224.  I cannot see how last or *argv is being freed.

description: The right operand of '<' is a garbage value

investigation.notes: first is thought to contain garbage.  Looking at the clang trace, it seems that first is being populated by fill_bounds
investigation.old_notes: start is thought to be garbage.  There is a long ste of conditions starting from 2455 that assign to start.  Interestingly, the declaration on 2447 only initializes stop but not start, though the first conditional 2455 always sets start to either sector_offset or extended_offset + sector_offset.  Sector offset seems to be defined, albeit confusing, with the INIT_G macro.  extended_offset, however, is not initialized in the same way.  The question is then is it initialized whenever the else branch of 2455 is set.  (Interesting that ENABLE_FEATURE_FDISK_WRITABLE controls a function that initializes extended_offset on line 1323.  Also interesting that there is a comment on 2510 checking if another value equsl extended_offset that says "must be corrected").

description: Attempt to free released memory

investigation.notes: 304 uses a macro to make obuf expand to ibuf  If 563 (the error) happens after 561 (which is conditioned on FLAG_TWOBUFS), then the double free can happen.  FLAG_TWOBUFS enum value is multiplied by ENABLE_FEATURE_DD_IBS_OBS, which, if not enabled, is also reponsible for the the obuf to ibuf macro.  So it seems that if ENABLE_FEATURE_DD_IBS_OBS is enabled, then obuf != ibuf, and the condition leading to 563 can happen.  If not enabled, the condition leading to 563 cannot happen even though ibuf and obuf are the same.

description: Null pointer passed as an argument to a 'nonnull' parameter

investigation.notes: encode_then_expand_string initializes dest to a NULL_O_STRING (NULL struct with first field being data).  This is passed to encode_string to be populated.  encode_string, if it fails to read a character, will return without populating the data field.  There is a comment "//TODO: error check (encode_string returns 0 on error)?" that seems to corraborate that this is possible.  Then expand_string_to_string is called on dest.data, which can be NULL.  Then expand_string_to_string uses strchr on this value.
